## 5. Backward Compatibility Strategy

To avoid breaking any pre-existing imports or endpoint registrations in other parts of the monorepo (such as booking management, review controllers, or index mounts) we will deploy **Proxy Files** at the old file paths:

### 1. Route Entry Proxy
We keep [backend/src/routes/auth.js](file:///c:/Users/bibha/Desktop/sahayog-sarthi/backend/src/routes/auth.js) in place, but empty its routing logic and change it to export the new clean router:
```javascript
// backend/src/routes/auth.js (Proxy Wrapper)
import authRoutes from '../modules/auth/interfaces/routes/authRoutes.js';
export default authRoutes;
```
This ensures `index.js` mounts the routing gate cleanly without any modifications.

### 2. Mongoose Model Proxies
To prevent breaking import statements like `import User from '../models/User.js';` in controllers such as payments or bookings, we keep `backend/src/models/User.js` and `backend/src/models/Worker.js` in place as proxy wrappers:
```javascript
// backend/src/models/User.js (Proxy Wrapper)
import User from '../modules/auth/infrastructure/persistence/schemas/UserSchema.js';
export default User;
```
```javascript
// backend/src/models/Worker.js (Proxy Wrapper)
import Worker from '../modules/auth/infrastructure/persistence/schemas/WorkerSchema.js';
export default Worker;
```

This guarantees 100% backward compatibility and enables us to refactor other modules incrementally in subsequent phases.
